Feature: the bc-emit work-done wrapper's refusal error directs the BC to self-resolve its OWN bead/commit state and re-emit, and NEVER names the lead as the actor for BC-repo state

  Pins the named-cause error-text posture that lead-vhfa defect 2 identifies, as a
  behavior of the CLI-layer "bc-emit work-done" wrapper (ADR-036 D1/D2). The defect:
  a pre-emit gate refusal carried text instructing "Router must commit/push ... and
  reconcile", improperly punting BC-repo housekeeping to the lead. This is wrong on
  two counts: (a) per ADR-018 the lead never commits BC repos — there is no
  lead-side BC source to commit; (b) per BC self-resolve discipline the BC MUST
  resolve its own clean-tree / commit state before emitting, never punt it to the
  lead.

  This scenario pins that on ANY refusal (clean-tree, commit-on-origin-main,
  tag-reachability, or scenario_hashes-match), the wrapper's named-cause error
  directs the BC to self-resolve its OWN bead/commit/working-tree state and re-emit,
  and the error text never instructs or implies that the lead (or "router") should
  commit, push, or otherwise act on BC-repo state. The prose-layer cousin of this
  self-resolve discipline (bc-implementer/bc-reviewer template prose, lead-oyaj)
  stays a separate judgment-layer pin (ADR-036 D1) and is not pinned here.

  The wrapper runs inside the BC container against the BC's own tree (ADR-036 D2,
  ADR-018). "shop-msg respond" stays a pure messaging primitive; the bare "--force"
  path (scenario 181) remains the escape valve.

  @scenario_hash:4a6133f7b5f061a2
  Scenario: on any bc-emit work-done precondition refusal the named-cause error directs the BC to self-resolve its own state and re-emit, and never names the lead or router as the actor for BC-repo state
    Given the "bc-emit work-done" wrapper refuses an emit on any of its preconditions — clean-working-tree, work_id-commit-on-origin-main, tag-deliverable reachability, or scenario_hashes-match
    When the BC reads the wrapper's named-cause error text
    Then the error directs the BC to self-resolve its OWN bead, commit, and working-tree state — committing its own changes or correcting its own hashes — and then to re-invoke "bc-emit work-done"
    And the error text does NOT instruct, request, or imply that the lead, the router, or any non-BC actor should commit, push, or reconcile the BC's repository state
